Thank you, so 12 seconds and can you explain the incentive per block is calculated on an individual miner basis? what calculation is used to determine how much of the incentive you receive?

R = W^T * S
T = (W >0).int() ^ T * S
deltaB = W^T x S
B = B + delta B 
C = sig( 10 * ( T - 0.5 ) )
I = R * C
D = B/B_1 x I
E = D
Read the paper for more details.
Or the code step function in opentensor/subtensor/pallets/subtensor/src/lib.rs

Good point. Forgot to add that part in the command. Would need to include " --axon.port 8040" for each command but with a 10 digit differentiation from what I have been told for each one (I.e. 8040, 8050, 8060, 8070)

The port numbers just have to be different and not in use by other network traffic.  IE. 8091, 8092, 8093, 8094, etc  would work as well.  The valid range of TCP/UDP is 1 - 65535, however the 1-1024 ports are reserved, and many ports from 1025 - 65535 are used for other services.  For example, Atlassian Confluence has a default port of 8090, Couchbase Web Admin and API use 8091 8092 respectively.
Interesting. Is there a way to check which ports are preferable to run the miner on and which are being used for other services? Also, is it ok for multiple peers to all be using the same port?

Yeah, you can definitely nerd out on networking, but the main idea is that each IP address and port combination should be unique.  For the VPS that I am using, I only have to concern myself with what I am running on it.  So, I knew I could use 8091, 8092, etc because I wasn't running something else that would conflict.
When you define the Axon port, you advertising where you want to be contacted from the internet.

It isn't clear how exactly we could copy across, for instance, we could keep the local head weights directly copied and only train the local-base with distillation. However then the local-head can't adapt to the shift caused by distillation nor the standard loss. Alternatively we could train the head after with fine tuning.
@Taco

I'm in favor of testing whether a single head (TransformerEncoder+decoder) for both local and remote would work, it ought to. We can train it only for remote since it represents the ideal input to the head, which local is yet to learn, but it can get a head start (pun intended). It is the simplest most straightforward I think, since the neuron ought to have the same task for both remote and local they may as well share the task head.
